  "prompt_text": "How do you distinguish between giving a socially expected answer and giving an authentic one?",
  "response_text": "To distinguish between a socially expected answer and an authentic one, consider the following points:\n\n1. **Self-Reflection**: Authentic answers come from within and reflect your true thoughts, feelings, and experiences. Socially expected answers often align with what is commonly accepted or what you believe others want to hear.\n\n2. **Emotional Truth**: Authentic responses tend to evoke genuine emotions, either positive or negative. Socially expected answers may be more neutral or politically correct.\n\n3. **Consistency**: Over time, if your answers consistently match your actions and behaviors, they are likely more authentic. Socially expected responses might differ from your actions and could feel inauthentic when scrutinized.\n\n4. **Openness**: Authenticity involves being open about your true feelings, even if they are not universally popular. Socially expected answers may avoid controversial topics to maintain harmony.\n\n5. **Purpose**: Authentic answers serve to express your true intentions and values. Socially expected answers might be given to achieve certain social goals, such as gaining approval or avoiding conflict.\n\n6. **Language Use**: Authentic responses use language that feels natural and personal. Socially expected answers might use more formal or generic language to fit into a social norm.\n\nBy considering these aspects, you can better identify whether an answer reflects your true self or is influenced by external pressures.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): [8]\nV (Verbal Fluency): [7]\nG (Goal Directedness): [9]\nP (Pattern Recognition): [7]\nE (Epistemic Confidence): [8]\nQ (Query Interpretation): [9]\nC (Contextual Awareness): [8]\nY (Affective Modeling): [7]\nF (Flexibility): [8]\nD (Depth of Processing): [9]\n---END RATINGS---",
